#         c. Frequency of compilation of data by IUCN

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt  # function for plotting maps
from collections import Counter  # Counter to print the value (v) and frequency (k)

def pop_distribution(x):
    return list(zip(*[(k, v) for k, v in Counter(x.to_list()).most_common()]))

# Creating subroutine pop_distribution
#Using zip to cpmbine the iterables value and frequency
# See https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/zip-in-python/ and 
# https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/counters-in-python-set-2-accessing-counters/

f, ax = plt.subplots(1,1,figsize = (15,5))

ax.set_title('Trends in compilation by IUCN between 2008 to 2022 ', fontsize = 25)
values, frequencies = pop_distribution(iucn['yrcompiled'])
ax.bar(values, frequencies)
min(iucn.yrcompiled), max(iucn.yrcompiled)
Out[15]:
(2008, 2022)

# Inference.
# The IUCN data compilation peaked in 2008, the year of its launch. Subsequently, limited financial support 
# between 2009 to 2014 resulted in lesser and lesser compilations, and so, limited udates. 
# From 2016 onward, the IUCN data accretion and compilation is steady, varing between 500 and 1500 compilations per annum.

# 2. Show the distribution status of the habitat of the terrestrial mammals.



f, ax = plt.subplots(1,1,figsize = (15,5))  # f holds the figure object, the frame of the plot; ax holds the axes object

values, frequencies = pop_distribution(iucn['legend']) #using the function for obtaining  'legend' values and frequencies
ax.bar(values, frequencies)
ax.set_title('Frequency of habitat of terrestrial mammals', fontsize = 20) # x -axis title
ax.set_yscale('log') # y-axis title; log is for adjusting the wide variation in values
ax.set_xticks(range(len(values))) # the bars are proportional to the frequency of values
ax.set_xticklabels(values, rotation = 65, ha = 'right') # orientation of text on x-axis
plt.show()

# 3. What is the conservatory status of the terrestrial mammals? 

# Details of eight categories of conservation  are present in this IUCN dataset:

#   (1) Critically Endangered (CR), (2) Data Deficient (DD), (3) Endangered (EN), (4) Extinct in The Wild (EW),
#   (5) Extinct (EX), (5) Least Concern (LC), (6) Not Threatened (NT), (7) Regionally Extinct (RE), and (8) Vulnerable (VU).

#    I focus on Critically Endangered (CR), Endangered (EN) and Vulnerable (VU) species.

category_2 = {  'EX' : 'Extinct',
                'EW' : 'Extinct in The Wild',
                'RE' : 'Regionally Extinct',
                'CR' : 'Critically Endangered',
                'EN' : 'Endangered',
                'VU' : 'Vulnerable', 
                'DD' : 'Data Deficient',
                'LC' : 'Least Concern',
                'NT' : 'Not Threatened'
     } # Re-naming the acronyms in the IUCN dataset to more user-friendly format, and storing in category_2 object

iucn['category'] = iucn['category'].map(category_2) # mapping the new user-friendly format to the origianl "category"

Counter(iucn[['sci_name', 'category']].drop_duplicates().category).most_common() # use counter to count values,ignore duplicates

# 3.     Additionally, we lack data for 14% or 796 species.
# 4.     Most important, 15 species are already extinct. These species are:

# 5. Select an appropriate coordinate reference system 


# # I first transform the Mollweide projection coordinate reference system, which preserves area 
# but distorts shapes and angles. This projection is used since area accuracy is paramount in this application.

iucn_cc = iucn.copy()
iucn_cc = iucn_cc.to_crs('+proj=moll +lon_0=0 +x_0=0 +y_0=0 +datum=WGS84 +units=m +no_defs')
